The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as it published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually of advanced age, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "turn" witches are sent to an isolated area, so they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such a thing."
"Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help in the work and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, is occupied in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a catch.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso don’t know how to read,” warns Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week in Ghana, a neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman got stuck in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “Human soul eaters have always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president was still involved in it.
Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by means of black magic.
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the President’s personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly chosen from among the Gambian peoples to the President’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the detainees did not survive the stay on the farm.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
Bakala tenant: heats up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, aged and young, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "coal magnate" Zden<0xC4><0x9B>k Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-story lease agreements: his own, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving sentence.
All three have just been caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 CZK a month, the son will pay 4,100 CZK from next year for a two-room apartment with a second-category separate kitchen.
"Furthermore, there is no hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man points out in his son's new contract, over which he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains, half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which rated the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, the date on which it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, before this, man only makes one ademan.
"Everything says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major testing laboratory for liberalization.
After the New Year will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktualn<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a number picking machine.
"Rental 2011", can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When pressing it, a little paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to even read "157" and already the number appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Shortly thereafter, an older marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd of the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues, and similar issues.
Letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the tenants’ mailboxes of most of the 44,000 RPG-owned floors around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers you in the cards a rental increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens at the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been running for a week, so it’s starting,” they answer, after briefly doubting, the workers who are in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
The liberalization and old mining floors of Bakala are the most delicate issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were treated loud and clear by the Vice-President of the Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, and now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change my damn bathroom plate," the man mentioned in the introduction says.
According to the workers, for the moment, more than anything retired come to check if they receive a discount on the rental if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half the discount on the February rental.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked for the rental in 2011 about forty or fifty people,” estimates the window employee.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to conduct individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rental, an independent judge will have to settle the matter.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed possible and fully compliant with the law," RPG said in a statement.
“Nobody is going to be judged here,” says one of RPG Byty’s employees, and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I get a 13,000 pension and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court," he says.
But immediately, the employee sows the doubt.
"We'll see."
