Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“Current rentals still don’t even cover the amounts needed to maintain the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio at RPG Byty, adding that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years that elapsed between 2005 and 2010, RPG was able with rents to invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014, the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, facing the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some highlighting data in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"Furthermore, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per month per square meter," the screen reads.
Just increase by 38% the rental of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter," RPG says.
On 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not immediately affect rents, but will escalate in four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rental increase (see the chart) back in the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rental increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that there is also a small nursery with everything specific to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio numerous well-known buildings of Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-kindergarten.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers as part of its social program.
Constructors and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini nursery was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-kindergarten is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), the company Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-kindergarten running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project took one year and the company Economy Rating contributed in the submission of the application for funding.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified personnel; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The kindergarten currently welcomes children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-kindergarten", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is a teaching and individual care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten program are comparable to the usual pre-school education program.
In it, children not only play, but also receive a quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive atmosphere.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive when they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design ranks among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened staff marketing.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its shape similar to a skeleton, locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all of which are typical of Antoni Gaudí’s secession.
The cover of the house plays with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought out order is observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the ornaments of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, arose from the renovation of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of performing a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project ornaments appeared for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and the Güell Park of Gaudí, in which there are other pieces of the same.
Due to its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of the yawning".
It is also said that, at the top of the building, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating era with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its forty-five-degree inclination may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the building rules of the moment and did not let himself be influenced by them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, upon its completion, the city council was so impacted with the result that it asked for it to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
Arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the request from the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
On the lower floors was installed the owner himself.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connection of space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can thus communicate seamlessly, without renouncing the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with the light, white and blue tiles that cover the courtyard and candlesticks.
The game with the two colors brings maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and refilled apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the loft, including the roof terrace.
The price of admission to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry of other Gaudí constructions into the city.
