How to choose the mattress and somier: women and men look for different things
Nothing like a pompous frame for the bed; what really gives its quality to a good bed is the surface to lie down, i.e. the mattress and the sommer.
First of all, they must be complemented perfectly so that they are adapted to specific users.
During the choice, numerous elements come into play, including the weight, height, health status and sex of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and mattress is placed.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that is usually not heated, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat" more slowly.
In addition, they tend to weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them around more often.
If the channels of the center are not properly aerated and, above, are on a firm base, they keep moisture inside.
When it comes to choosing a bed, customs are also influenced.
Those who have spent a lot of time abroad often use a very tall mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower and harder surface.
“Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn’t sleep as well here.”
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"This type of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have time problems with the nervous system, so they receive poorly information from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem anymore, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italians Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelasticity.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not turn around like after a hard game.
It just sleeps better.
Viscoelastic also works as a protection against wounds.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to your height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of about 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, a total of 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example single rooms, a minimum of 120 to 140 cm is recommended.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when lying face up, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk towards the elbows," advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert of Cechu <0xC4><0x8C>alouník<0xC5><0xAF> a dekoratér<0xC5><0xAF>, who has been dealing with the problem of healthy sleep and ergonomics in furniture for many years.
In the double rooms, each one needs its own somier and mattress, so during the purchase you need to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the beds at different heights, which is not always possible on all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with interior springs a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
"When you touch it with your hand or sit on the mattress, you should definitely not notice the springs," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of somier.
The fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, make no sense in the bedroom.
The mattresses breathe badly and you can not wash your sleeve, which is often done today.
And, since every night we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that talk about a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime warranty.
However, everything has a but.
That is why sellers give advice: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care of the cleaning and washing of the cover, but it is better to add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although zippered mattress covers are currently manufactured throughout their perimeter, so when opened they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their handling on larger models (and by one person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a fly weight and a weight.
In bed, instead of a dreamer, does he have a firm table?
Never, never!
As much for the beds designed for one night visits.
However, it should make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes in the table and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulated sheet beds containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (e.g., a combination of latex and coconut fiber) may be used, although it is always better to use a bed with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the stiffened lumbar area sheets may be reinforced.
Articulable sheet beds should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the rigidity of the sheets, shoulder protection can also be used.
This is a special fixation of the sheets that allows you to press or even tilt the sheets in such a way that they "round" perfectly to the shoulders during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is something very important.
They are even remembered by the mattress makers who, in the "male", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are cross structured or tray beds with the so-called multitorsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the voltage is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that even if you use the right mattress and soother, if you use a bad pillow (large and "mulled"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should hold the head and the corners can only reach to the shoulders, so that the muscles of the same can be relaxed.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on the side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder pad or the softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses seem to have something to do with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, organic mattresses are fashionable.
The petroleum-based raw materials with which the polyurethane foam is made are filled with natural oils, e.g. castor or soybean.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soybeans.
"Biologically, in the case of mattresses, it means that the center is made exclusively of natural materials," explains Petr Va<0xC5><0xA1>í<0xC4><0x8D>ek of Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma to forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "refresh" themselves with brise vegetable extracts, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and cools the body, women prefer to "warm" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so women feel more warmth.
Favorites nowadays?
The mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various rigidities of cold and viscoelastic foam makes it possible to manufacture mattresses from various areas that perfectly know where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns upwards.
Those who perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as medical means.
The first to get this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and soothers.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a Memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 crowns.
The second one is available for free.
The era of viscoelastics with an open cellular structure and high density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
Initially it emerged as material for NASA, because during the takeoffs the astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with the heat and hardens with the cold.
Therefore, the warm human body exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Viscoelastic foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents are using people tracking devices to control their children
The fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in the case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a lighter box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were frightened by the case of the missing Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
“We’re all trying to tell ourselves that it’s not about spying, but another way to lessen the chances of a tragedy happening,” says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the tracking device suppliers in the Czech market.
“I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone’s pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases.”
“Most customers actually buy it for safety reasons,” adds Pilin.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even the youngest children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to prevent them from being controlled.”
"In the past, parents relied heavily on mobiles, but these could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," says Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková.
In his opinion, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
“If it’s a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check if the child is carrying some kind of electronic device that can reveal their location.”
"Now it's the phone."
“As the use of tracking devices expands, you will also look for them, as their sale will undoubtedly be made with a lot of advertising.”
“In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the event of an impromptu attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert <0xC4><0x8C>ech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can be helpful.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If it suffers damage, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question."
“The most expensive devices have an integrated tilt gauge, so if the person simply slips and stays motionless, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says <0xC4><0x8C>ech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smartphones with navigation, on which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that they are currently devices with a similar size to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, for this reason, tests are currently being carried out with devices that resemble a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential aggressor may not identify the device."
“Or identify it after a certain amount of time, which can make the police gain time,” he adds.
Although the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology that is used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position check with a GPS system (used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough mechas to surround the entire Czech Republic. But they only last two years
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to hold explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of mecha to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the service life of the wick is two years, four at the most.
The army bought the wick for explosives from STV Group, a.s. for forty million crowns.
The General’s staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of mica saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of mica per year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnicians of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided, however, that, in such a case, should carry out such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high-ranking officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want exemptions even the Minister of Defense Alexandr Vondr and the army captain Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could it be justified for the army to spend sixty kilometers of wick.
This is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have sufficient stockpiles for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of mecha, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stock for the 225 indicated above.
Soldiers of the rapid-intervention brigade recently personally complained to Minister Vondra because they say they have barely ammunition for various weapons, so even the practice of firing for money is limited.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also fail to understand that we are repeatedly bought such amounts of mica."
“But it’s their decision and they’ll definitely know why they act like that.”
"For us, the army is a good customer that we, as a company, try to satisfy," admits Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>, the commercial director of STV Group.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defends the hundreds of miles of mecha, saying he will also have stockpiles of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>, of STV Group, indicates that the wick has a shelf life of only four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, two years.
“If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four,” says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition should be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument from the Ministry is that, when buying 445 kilometers of mica, it got a discount.
“They cost us 60% less than last year’s order of 244 kilometers,” said Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defense’s shopping centre.
Just to compare: the annual consumption of mica by police pyrotechnicians, who eliminated World War II ammunition or left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask for only the right amount to deplete the ammunition before its service life runs out.
They decided for safety reasons for pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable types of wicks can be obtained.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand people was preparing for a campaign in the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: you will have to remove hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "cheap".
