Families will have to pay extra expenses of several hundred crowns per month
Households will have to pay from January not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, larger rentals.
As a result, families will have to withdraw several hundred kroner a month from the portfolio, starting in January, more than now.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, gas by about 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for the water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The rise in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 crowns more per year than now.
However, major electricity suppliers have lowered prices, due to increased support for the production of energy from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaic.
However, the gas is costing moderately, especially at the time when heating is used the most and, therefore, consumption is higher.
In this case, they should also have a couple hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are rising across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The increase in prices is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay an additional 50 kronor per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay an additional 1,000 kronor per year.
Residents in Prague will also face a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rental of infrastructure.
If the rent does not vary, the Praguens will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will continue to be among the lowest in the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will increase by 7.4%.
The prices of 450,000 leased flats in Prague, where the regulation will end in January, can increase considerably.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 floors in <0xC3><0x9A>stí nad Labem, will increase rent by up to 100% from January.
The company will take to the courts those who disagree with the new lease.
Regulated rentals, which benefit residents of around 300,000 floors, could increase next year by up to 10%.
Young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. Beer is no longer in mode, because it works slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get them drunk."
"Now, strong alcoholic beverages are fashionable," says Lud<0xC4><0x9B>k Pelikán, head of pediatrics at the Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice Hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to get a bottle from their father from the casserole, it can be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage of lightening with juice and not smelling so much,” he explains.
It is also confirmed by the spokeswoman of the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
“These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren.”
"In some cases, they use water that they took at home," Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikan, it is thirteen and fourteen-year-olds who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice, where he has been working since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics at Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times."
"It started at the age of twelve, when they brought it with 3.5 of blood alcohol, plus a mixture with ecstasy," the department's doctor said.
"He was at the Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that his mother wasn't even surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours," he said.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance for drinking on the part of their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot speak properly of dependence.
"Alcoholic is a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
“In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment,” explains Chief Pelikan.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinová, this year in Motol pediatric clinic were hospitalized until mid-November forty drunk children.
However, statistics show only those who come with severe intoxication and must stay in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after a medical on-the-go examination, go home with their parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink water, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that should be mentioned: Halloween, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for the bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"On the day of the witches I have come to see in admissions up to seven drunk children at a time," adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is prevented by injecting a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"These take it much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and it hurts them nothing."
“They only show up confused about where they are,” says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose good humor at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
The transfer by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients comes to cost about ten thousand crowns.
“I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell them directly to the children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job so that you would earn enough to pay for yourself that night,” Pelikán adds.
Health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a retrospective measure, which usually returns people the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
