The first is the relatively lively humor prevailing in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6% annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a reduced 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a major decline in production last year.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Chart 2).
Around 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably above the 25 per cent recorded in 2001 (Figure 3).
Around 34 per cent said they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has persisted during the global financial crisis is probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only marginally increased in 2009 and has declined again this year, to 32%.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see chart 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since surveys began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Chart 5).
Around 31 per cent say they or a close relative have been victims of crime in the past year, a figure that has fallen from 38 per cent last year and is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71 per cent of respondents in the region say that private enterprises are indispensable for development, compared to only 56 per cent in 2007 (see Figure 6).
Around 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62 percent of Venezuelans say the same (and 80 percent support private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the greatest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
Elections to garbage
No one expected the general elections held on 28 November in Haiti to be perfect.
However, they went much worse than foreigners feared trying to help the country recover from its troubles.
Votes were introduced in the polls, some people voted several times, ballot papers dropped in the sewers, electoral colleges destroyed and acts of intimidation.
The electoral colleges opened with hours of delay.
Numerous Haitians, including groups displaced by the January earthquake, roamed the area trying to figure out where to vote.
Some of them, in the end, gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several of the most popular, reported fraud and called for the election to be cancelled.
The protests, some of them violent, spread throughout the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the highest-ranking United Nations official in Haiti, said they were "relatively good choices in many ways."
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community cautiously stated that “we do not believe that these irregularities, however serious, necessarily invalidate the process.”
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, which according to its opponents is committed to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and to his candidate, Jude Célestin, should announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The match is expected to take place in January.
All hope has not yet been lost in connection with the elections.
The two main opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rapper, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, have withdrawn their initial petition requesting the invalidation of the vote.
But problems can still arise if the electoral authority declares that Mr Célestin, who has hardly any support, if he has any, has passed to the second round.
Given that the cholera epidemic is devastating the country and more than a million of the earthquake survivors are still living in stores, a large abstention is expected.
When the time came, many Haitians wanted to vote, but failed to do so due to a lack of organization.
Around 250,000 identity documents, required to vote, had not yet been distributed shortly before the elections.
There's a lot at stake.
Donors believe that the election of a legitimate and popular government is an essential step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And, as has been evident, the Haitians themselves think so.
