In the weeks that have elapsed since she lost her husband, Cristina Fernández, the president of Argentina, has enjoyed a great sympathy among the public that has increased its popularity index by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level it has recorded since its election in 2007.
Despite all this, it will depend on whether the clearly affected Ms. Fernández puts aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are not conclusive.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to take charge of economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, was accustomed to drafting budgets that undervalued tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential marriage to spend additional income at its discretion.
In theory, Mrs. Fernandez’s government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened since Kirchner’s death due to a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissident members of the Peronist movement in power have faced Mrs. Fernández.
However, after chaotic sessions in which one MP punched another in the face and other MPs accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue," the president said.
Accordingly, the 2010 budget will be applied to the coming year, giving the President even more room for action when it comes to spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it is likely to grow up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1%, but numerous private calculations, in addition to the wage requirements of the trade unions, place it close to 30%.
