A more moderate side of law enforcement in China is promoted
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin made his way to a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of Chengguan, the corpulent police officers of China’s urban order, feared and despised for their capricious energetic measures and their inclination to violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Firms!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "how beautiful the girls are!"
Four girls who barely spent adolescence with identical white gloves and olive green jackets and tight pants to draw attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed on top of the hair tied with blue and white striped mouldings.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance," Mr. Tang said, scornfully.
“The models are beautiful.”
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
A city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
The Guangdong Province changed the grayish-green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating glances: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a snack cart, and watched it with the cheek constantly frowned for half an hour, until the strolling salesman picked up his belongings and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 inhabitants in Chengdu, has chosen a radical change of image.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, expressly chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rude police a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s petty respect for these city squadrons.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province beat a passerby to death after he used his cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and published on the Internet, describing how to effectively whip criminals without making them bleed.
This year, a traveling melon seller from Shanghai suffered brain damage after a quarrel with five officers.
A video game full of violence, available for download online, introduces Chinese-trained inspectors who attack street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar in the government,” lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded “a really meticulous cleaning.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
