“Most of the time it’s the audience that starts the fight.”
Prosecutors will not raise charges against Senator Ensign
The senator’s lawyers announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have acquitted Senator John Ensign of the criminal charges arising from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure work through lobbying for the woman’s husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair had national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said it felt "certainly happy" with the decision, which came after a year-long investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary measure from the Senate Ethics Committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer an objective of his investigation and that he has no plan to raise charges against him on this issue.”
The Department of Justice declined to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign might have conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, email and other documents that were first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, get lucrative work through lobbying, to achieve Hampton's silence and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr. Hampton and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was barred under the law from lobbying for his former employer or Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called “revolving door lobbying ban,” which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, “it seemed to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door status,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department seemed cautious in accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year's decision to abandon prosecution by Steve Sen.
Federal prosecutors “are clearly cowards,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Accountability and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
“This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws don’t apply to them,” he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s chief attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to raise charges against his client.
Ensign’s defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Coggins declined to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to prosecutors.
“I don’t feel comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we thought they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, alleging that a $96,000 payment from Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was just a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got a job through lobbying thanks to the help Ensign gave Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him that he was "knocking" the Interior Ministry on a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and called the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he hired Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the affair first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign spokeswoman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, she said the senator expected the ethics committee to quickly follow the Department of Justice’s lead and complete its investigation.
"Senator Ensign has a desire to continue his difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada," he said.
Cheshire Appeal Will Target Twitter
There were half a dozen of them "chatting" in the ranks of the courtroom.
Minute by minute, they sent reports of the appalling testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense says, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the process that addressed the rape and the children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely-followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a Cheshire, Connecticut family, is set to come to an official conclusion, with the judge’s imposition of the death penalty voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have filed letters in court outlining the arguments of appeals likely to occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims is that the intense reports on the process, including the widespread use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created “a circus atmosphere,” and such widespread and immediate saturation with exhilarating details caused public passions to exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appeal judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
“According to what I experienced during this process, I think there is a real danger that the inclusion of new technology in the courtroom is affecting the individual’s rights to have a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, senior defense attorney for Mr. Hayes.
Chief Justice Jon C. Blue, of the State Superior Court, laconically rejected the claims in a ruling last week, saying the media were “carefully controlled” and there was no evidence that the jury was carried by the passion.
But it probably won’t be the last word on the subject.
For decades, appeals courts have recognized that coverage of famous cases can raise questions about the impartiality of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in his decision, in the Sheppard v. Maxwell case, that there was "an atmosphere of carnival in the process" due to the media.
It is believed that the crime was inspired by the TV show and the movie "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers said the appeals courts that examined Mr. Hayes’ conviction half a century later might be intrigued by the argument that new rules might be needed to control the form of communication from the courtrooms, something unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard’s case.
“There is a general reason for concern about the impact of the new media” on high-profile processes, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School, who studied the Connecticut death penalty and wrote a report saying it was imposed arbitrarily.
Professor Donohue said some appeals judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting immediate communication from courtrooms could make trials more fair.
The Twitter issue is just one of many issues outlined by Hayes’ lawyers, which will likely be discussed for years, delaying an execution.
Defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Hayes could have been harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors, showing them horrifying photographs of the crime scene during jury selection.
Some jurors have said they were horrified by the photographs of the victims, 48-year-old Jennifer Hawke-Petit and her daughters, 17-year-old Hayley and 11-year-old Michaela.
Defense lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge incorrectly removed a jury that had criticized prosecutors, and that he had incorrectly pressed for a verdict for his strange decision to order the jury to deliberate over a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But his arguments about the effect of intense process coverage can attract most interest.
They observed in a rejection to the filing verdict last month that the case dominated news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media continually cast fire to the fire of emotion on the case.
“The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the courthouse,” the lawyers wrote, “was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps across the state.”
Their attention in the coverage of Tweeter is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that the complaint that the immediate news was more important than the reports delivered more slowly was a ludicrous view that would make the court’s policy on coverage control weak in future trials.
But some lawyers said appeal courts often felt attracted by the arguments about adaptation required in courts due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pressing for that claim.
In their writing, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, which revoked Dr. Sheppard’s conviction due to the coverage of the trial, and made clear that they would require that the new media require new rules.
“This case,” they wrote, “represents the 21st century Sheppard vs. Maxwell case.”
Can civility stretch a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, this week has sparked a bit of civility in Washington.
Is it a foreshadowing of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a swift return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders yielded no progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But as they all say, it was at least a courteous discussion about the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite remaining political differences between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a trial period, probing each other to identify signs of co-operativeness and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voters’ patience for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent evaluations of the same by the participants were done with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed with respect to the way things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which then extinguish.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, there is likely to be a commitment to extending unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can’t make people believe they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s White House meeting, there is increased optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontational one,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012.”
The motives have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises of cutting state spending and nullifying the new health law.
Those support lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have handled one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forced the issue of the deficit into the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials in the panel, suggesting that on tax issues there are, at least at present, few bases or desire for engagement.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama over budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as it happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they are losing will likely change course and seek engagement.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as a paradise of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a “cleptocracy,” leaving a portion of the bribes and protection money directly to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service handle huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Every stratum of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has dubbed the “vertical authority,” takes its share as money rises on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blamed him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have consistently denied allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several lawsuits for libel over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested he was corrupt, he said: “It’s crazy, it’s bullshit, it’s annoying.”
According to surveys, the Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of for diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
“The direct links of the Moscow City government with crime have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional’, and to claim that the government functions more like a cleptocracy than a government,” the statement said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term of the criminal world and the mafia that literally means ‘ceiling’ or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor’s office, as well as all sectors of the Moscow city government bureaucracy.
"Analysts identify a three-level structure in Moscow's criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The SFS, the MVD and the militia are on the second level."
“Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas, because the city does not provide some services.”
The report states that the SFS raises money from the largest companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report said, “explained that Moscow’s business owners understand that it is best to get protection from MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but they are also protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority.”
The note notes that while the collection of money is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who don’t pay quickly find their businesses closed for one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
"In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats," said Georgy Satarov, director of the Indem expert group in Moscow, in a recent interview.
"But he's a part of this bureaucracy."
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, corruption is inevitable.
Nationally, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154th (countries are ranked least to most corrupt).
The revelation of the U.S. Embassy note, which did not take place until late at night time in Moscow, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation claiming that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country,” he said.
"But to be honest with you, we do not suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would have been done in such an immoral way."
Veterans of the Red Khmers forced to face the past
In a poorly lit concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the director of the Anlong Veng Secondary School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Red Khmer Ta Mok.
"Everybody loves Ta Mok here."
“He was a good leader and cared for his people,” said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge government, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Khmers surrendered to the government, long-lasting loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Red Khmers to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint United Nations and Cambodia court issued the first sentence of a former member of the Red Khmers, sentenced the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the Anlong Veng Red Khmer veterans, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Red Khmers, but they can do nothing,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
"For them, life under the Red Khmers was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
“This is creating divisions within families.”
During the reign of the Cambodian Red Khmers, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, illness or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government in 1979, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to Cambodia's border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla warfare from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began deserting to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the shallow soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have gained little benefit after surrender," said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
“They were raised with no concept of doing business.”
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating herself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Red Khmers was fine," he said.
"Ta Mok gave them all to eat."
"But now life is hard because we have to self-supply."
The current Khmer Rouge court has also raised concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former minister of the Khmer Rouge.
The court’s mandate is to prosecute the top leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases in addition to those four.
This did not serve much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge government in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodian Documentation Center that she had supervised the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers are thought to have died.
During a recent muggy afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden piles on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Red Khmers.
She claimed that if the court summoned her, she would not appear.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," he said.
“If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who deserted the Red Khmers in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is precisely what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk, of the documentation center.
"The reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Red Khmers, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the High School History textbook of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Red Khmers.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little about the Red Khmers, despite the city’s link to the regime.
Toque Valeak, a 19-year-old student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court,” he said.
“They have suspicions because they are not sure about the number of people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Red Khmers retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a road with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of black smoke covered by an oxidized tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here over a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
