Shoebox and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to stay in the euro, but it has set the conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets have provoked a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or suppression of the 426 euros of aid to unemployed without benefit, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of State Lottery.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has added to the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
Go ahead that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another turning point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of much of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible exits to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budget rigour, fines to infringing countries, possible suspensions of payments from some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government pulled a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of a divergence between what Germany believed needed to be done (fiscal rigorous plans and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second in the front was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended Greece’s rescue decision.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion and the published opinion were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the EU treaties, to make it possible to save a country and, at the same time, force private lenders to run with part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been adopted and, in the coming months, we should attend the process of reforming the Union that will make those measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, although he now has to take measures with which he may not agree very much, from that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which infringing countries will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare themselves in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also run with part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not tolerate it.
The invitation is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand.
It is not just about bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand is much harder.
And the worst we could do under these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquility.
And let us take advantage of the window of opportunity that has been given to us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has understood this as well, and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis that it is necessary to put order at home has opened the way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn’t look like they’re going to move it.
And, among the possibilities envisaged, that of leaving a monetary zone too crowded of unserious countries, cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sports and Fraud
Fools like Alonso and Ramos at Ajax show ingenuity but not the will to escape a penalty.
The alleged expulsion of two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink rivers to be written about whether or not such behavior is anti-sporting and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, a few minutes away from finishing the game (which their team had clearly already won), the two players deliberately lost time in drawing wrong paths to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and can pass card cleansing to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team’s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches, and with different financial amounts the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been played by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and which in past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization, apparently by Mourinho, who adds a more technical episode to his story.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether such behavior, not expressly prohibited by the regulation, contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions commit fraud of the law; in fact, they are actions respectful of the sport regulation, but seem to circumvent its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that the sports spirit comprises is the physical integrity of the opposing players, aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with the clean game is to prevent the team of the offenders from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it did not conform to what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud, because his violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage offenders get in the deliberate wrongdoings examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that you do not put the opponent in a disadvantage situation or get a benefit in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the equipment can be eliminated at the first change, and in addition with this performance the players meet a penalty game and move to the second card cycle, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with a less than in the first cycle.
So, going rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sport, which is part of making strategic decisions that favor to make the most of what the rules allow.
In the case that concerns us, the players did not act to evade the enforcement of the penalty (this would be a clear case of fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the boundary between ingenuity and fraud is diffuse, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the transmission of the directive was carried out to provoke them.
The damage to the principles of sport caused by these actions is not both ethical and aesthetic.
