EU changes rules for obtaining visas
Individuals will need to go to Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower as well as the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa will change at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will need to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASC) before their interview at the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another more for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for cases of visas on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for merchants and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their footprints.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed at the Consular Section will stay at the ASC for less time than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
