At the center of this avalanche of more than a hundred contracts is a consortium formed by the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained without a prior tender the most important contract, the project management, for a sum of 295 million.
The consortium, called Énergie gérance, was created in 2004 following Hydro-Québec’s decision to entrust the private sector with its responsibility for managing this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the Énergie gérance consortium obtained the lucrative contract without a prior public tender.
For the Quebec Party, the use of corporate consortia poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and cause a rise in prices.
“This is a new method of collusion and elimination of competition.”
"That is, people, instead of doing it in secret, now openly do it," Quebec MP Sylvain Simard told a news conference.
Earlier in the morning, Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because, he says, he does not understand how the public interest can benefit in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, firmly denying that there has been a collusion with this contract.
“I’m starting to get tired,” he protested, defending that the PQ had acted “dishonestly” and “with a lack of rigor.”
He noted that "the minimum" would be for the PQ to apologize.
The consortium formula is a common practice around the world.
Typically, this is an alliance with a time limit that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project presents a high level of complexity, taking into account the magnitude of the works.
Work has already begun and will continue until 2012.
In any case, the contract was awarded without competition; it was a negotiation.
In addition, the consortium formula has ceased to be the exception to the norm in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir published last week, the formula of consortia in the technical advisory sector is being investigated by the government.
A quick look at Quebec’s trade register identifies more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
In this way, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Genivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal entity, i.e. Dessau.
