The WikiLeaks issue has a double value.
On the one hand, it unveils an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let’s go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of public knowledge news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for novelties about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to occultism not only trust what they already know, which confirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know what, the editor of Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same information that Newsweek published the previous week.
Then why have the revelations of these records caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of State can be called on the phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have been transformed into espionage centers.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows it perfectly, only we pretend we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secrets of the most powerful country in the world greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "verdugos".
But let’s get into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, he could conceive of himself as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power can escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circulating.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the citizen’s avenger) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets stand?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without a secret, since it comes from the public domain; but unveiling, as WikiLeaks has done, all the secrets of Hillary Clinton will mean.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the network, since it would be like posting it on a street sign.
But it’s also clear that, with current technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relations in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is science fiction and, therefore, novel, but I imagine government agents discreetly moving in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: ultimately, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a telegraph with cables (phones).
The videotapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, advancing and backwards, uncovering all the secrets of editing, while now the CDs (digital) only allow them to move forward or backwards from chapter to chapter, i.e. to huge proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the journeys it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was being secretly plotted in the embassies.
Today, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's plunder in its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked financing promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been met.
And the French chapuzas have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its member states, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparency was appreciated for what it really is: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on the right track towards meeting its commitment of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken the year 2009 as a reference: international financing is maintained and 150 million are added over three years in terms of fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
France, on the other hand, considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditure in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while purporting to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and each chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that every euro borrowed equals one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as the equivalent of a euro that is donated... At the very least, only the cost of the loan should be calculated for its commitments, the equivalent type of loan to the country that lends.
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see it for yourself.
It is the only country in the EU that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments to 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
That's a good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France commits a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions over time and, on the other hand, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he is spending 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other member states continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The chapter on early funding is a minutiae, relatively short-term, in relation to the whole of the climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of meeting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move the debate on stakes at stake in relation to long-term financing forward (another essential chapter that is currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of the “additional character” and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals in one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a ten-year-old child usually consumes in four meals and a snack a day.
These meals taken as a model, which adhere to official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as the treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The plate balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
“While, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each chemical individually are not exceeded, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is worrying,” the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a school snack, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, including in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian fillet, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were sticky with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most “nutritious” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk generated by these “contaminant cocktails” to the consumer is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in view of the gravity of the situation" to implement a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
